Commentary Text: Ashwin to Pollard, out Caught by Rabada! Delhi are roaring back! This was a pressure catch, check, and a brave ball for an off-break bowler to Kieron frickin' Pollard, check. Tosses this up from round the wicket, Pollard tries mowing this one in signature fashion over long-on, but to everyone's surprise, I suspect, he's not made good enough contact - Rabada runs forward from long-on, and dives forward to hold onto a terrific catch to get rid of the imperious Kieron Pollard. Pollard c Rabada b Ashwin 0(2)

Commentary Text: Nortje to Suryakumar Yadav, out Caught by Daniel Sams! Did you hear the grunt? He couldn't be more unimpressed with himself, Yadav. Bangs in the short ball right into the body at 143.8km/h, Suryakumar Yadav lays into the hook shot, but ends up getting more of a top-edge on it, which isn't going to carry over the boundary and goes straight to the man waiting at the fine leg fence - Daniel Sams. A loud grunt from Yadav translates to just how unimpressed he is with that shot - a hot-blooded one, that is unbecoming of a seasoned veteran - for the Mumbai Indians at least. Suryakumar Yadav c Daniel Sams b Nortje 51(38) [4s-6 6s-2]

Commentary Text: Ashwin to Rohit, out Lbw!! My my! DC got Ashwin to counter Quinton, but Ash's got the big fish. Who said offies to right-hander in this format is a no-no. This is just a flatter delivery from Ashwin, but it turned and surprised Rohit on the back foot defence. Missed a few games, hasn't had starts this season, and he misses a pretty straightforward delivery to be adjacent to the sticks. Plumb in front. Credit to Rohit for not eating the review just because he's the captain. Rohit lbw b Ashwin 0(1)

Commentary Text: Bumrah to Daniel Sams, out Caught by de Kock!! If you have pace and if you are bowling with big boundaries, the short ball can give you great success. Something Rabada and Nortje didn't do enough in their outing today. Commentary Text: Bumrah to Stoinis, out Bowled!! What do you mean, dew, tough for bowlers... Nonsense, is the response from Bumrah and you get that from his smile. 26th wicket - the most this IPL. Just a simple length ball you'd think, but it's Bumrah's awkward wide angle that is key to his success story. Stoinis thought he had the line covered for the back foot defence, until he heard the leg stump rattle out of the ground. Has to be the ticket for the final now for MI. Stoinis b Bumrah 65(46) [4s-6 6s-3]
